\subsubsection{Group}

An notable property missing from a monoid is the ability solve equations.  As an example,
take the 12-clock above.  Which of these equations can be solved:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Solve for $a$ in $a\times 3 = 7$.
\item Solve for $b$ in $4\times b = 8$.
\item Solve for $c$ in $7\times c = 11$.
\end{enumerate}

To solve such an equation we need to be able to find an inverse with
respect to the operation of the monoid.  Essential to the idea
of inverse is that an inverse be unique.

A monoid for which every element has a uniquie inverse is called
a group.


\begin{definition}[Group]
$(S,\circ)$ is called a \emph{group} if
\begin{enumerate}
\item $(S,\circ)$ is a monoid.
\item Inverse: $\forall a\in S~\exists a^{-1}\in S$ such that $a\circ a^{-1} = a^{-1} \circ a = e$
